column1: What is O(1) complexity?
column2: Constant — runtime doesn’t depend on input size. Example: Accessing an element in an array by index (arr[5])

column1: What is O(log n) complexity?
column2: Logarithmic — runtime grows proportionally to the logarithm of the input size. Example: Binary search.

column1: What is O(n) complexity?
column2: Linear —  runtime grows proportionally to the input size. Example: Traversing a list.

column1: What is O(n log n) complexity?
column2: Quasilinear — runtime grows proportionally to n times the logarithm of n. Example: Merge sort, heap sort.

column1: What is O(n^2) complexity?
column2: Quadratic — runtime grows proportionally to the square of the input size. Example: Nested loops, bubble sort.

column1: What is O(2^n) complexity?
column2: Exponential — runtime doubles with each additional input. Example: Tower of Hanoi, generating all subsets of a set.

column1: What is O(n!) complexity?
column2: Factorial — runtime grows factorially with the input size. Example: Permutations of a string.

column1: Rank the complexities from fastest to slowest.
column2: O(1) < O(log n) < O(n) < O(n log n) < O(n^2) < O(2^n) < O(n!).
